actually be a relief.
- The odds of winning...

95
00:07:44,897 --> 00:07:48,424
are a joke; you don't
have a chance in hell.

96
00:07:48,501 --> 00:07:52,301
I'm going, Mr. Goodman,
with or without your help.

97
00:07:54,206 --> 00:07:57,107
Call me from Jackson.
Don't thank me.

98
00:07:57,176 --> 00:07:59,406
I have not done you
a favor.

99
00:08:03,883 --> 00:08:05,817
- Did he do it?
- [Scoffs]

100
00:08:05,885 --> 00:08:10,652
Oh, he did it.
There's no question that he did it.

101
00:08:19,031 --> 00:08:21,022
[Woman On P.A.]
Your attention please.

102
00:08:21,100 --> 00:08:23,500
The Mississippi Scenic Cruiser
for downtown Jackson...

103
00:08:23,569 --> 00:08:25,833
is now boarding in the blue zone.

104
00:09:06,846 --> 00:09:09,542
- Good afternoon, sir.
Good to see you, sir.
- Thanks.

105
00:09:14,720 --> 00:09:16,654
[Doorbell Rings]

106
00:09:22,728 --> 00:09:25,663
[Guests Chattering]

107
00:09:33,772 --> 00:09:36,536
You look like
a mendicant Indian.

108
00:09:38,043 --> 00:09:39,977
[Laughs]

109
00:09:41,914 --> 00:09:44,178
Where is your luggage?
Jessie, help Mr. Hall with...

110
00:09:44,250 --> 00:09:46,548
Actually, I'm gonna stay
in a, uh, hotel near the courts.

111
00:09:46,619 --> 00:09:49,588
Um... I'm gonna be up all night,
workin' long hours, so...

112
00:09:49,655 --> 00:09:52,317
Oh, well, honey.
Whatever you like. I love you, you hear?

113
00:09:52,391 --> 00:09:55,588
Now you go freshen up and hurry down.
I have the mothers...

114
00:09:55,661 --> 00:09:59,358
of the only 12 remaining virgins
in all of Jackson...

115
00:09:59,431 --> 00:10:01,899
just panting to meet you.

116
00:10:01,967 --> 00:10:04,561
l-I really don't think I'm gonna have
too much time for socializing.

117
00:10:04,637 --> 00:10:08,198
You must regale us all with tales
of what it is that brings you here.

118
00:10:08,274 --> 00:10:11,368
I'm guessing it's to use
your lawyerly charms...

119
00:10:11,443 --> 00:10:14,879
to separate our local fat cats
from their ill-gotten fortunes.

120
00:10:14,947 --> 00:10:17,916
You should start
with my cranky old husband.

121
00:10:17,983 --> 00:10:20,281
He deserves
a good comeuppance.

122
00:10:20,352 --> 00:10:23,446
- Lee.
- Yes.

123
00:10:23,522 --> 00:10:26,423
I'm here to defend
your father.

124
00:10:28,827 --> 00:10:32,319
- Look, I understand that...
- You understand nothing.

125
00:10:32,398 --> 00:10:35,231
Don't you utter one word
to anyone.

126
00:10:35,301 --> 00:10:37,963
- Lee.
- Not one word.

127
00:10:39,038 --> 00:10:40,972
You hear?

128
00:10:52,885 --> 00:10:55,353
Good night. [Kiss]
Call me tomorrow.

129
00:10:55,421 --> 00:10:58,948
- I will.
- All right. Bye.

130
00:11:09,835 --> 00:11:11,803
- Lovely party, dear.
- Oh, thank you.

131
00:11:11,870 --> 00:11:14,896
Don't forget we have the museum
on Thursday.

132
00:11:14,974 --> 00:11:17,807
- Good night, Adam.
- Good night.

133
00:11:17,876 --> 00:11:19,810
Good luck.

134
00:11:23,349 --> 00:11:27,809
Phelps lives in town.
Oh, it's okay.

135
00:11:27,886 --> 00:11:31,322
We have a very active romantic life.
Just not with each other.

136
00:11:31,390 --> 00:11:33,187
Why stay married?

137
00:11:33,258 --> 00:11:37,126
Good for a banker to have
someone acceptable for social occasions.

138
00:11:37,196 --> 00:11:39,858
And it's good for you
to have a banker.

139
00:11:39,932 --> 00:11:43,299
Done pretty well
for poor white trash.

140
00:11:43,369 --> 00:11:45,303
Don't you think?

141
00:11:45,371 --> 00:11:48,431
Not bad.
Not bad at all.

142
00:11:48,507 --> 00:11:50,441
Of course, how acceptable
I'm gonna be...

143
00:11:50,509 --> 00:11:53,672
when the world finds out I'm
Hitler's daughter is another question.

144
00:11:53,746 --> 00:11:57,011
[Footsteps]

145
00:11:57,082 --> 00:12:00,313
It's all right.
It's under control.

146
00:12:00,386 --> 00:12:02,650
Nobody knows?

147
00:12:02,721 --> 00:12:05,781
Well, I was speakin'
of my drinkin'.

148
00:12:05,858 --> 00:12:08,622
But no.
No one knows.

149
00:12:08,694 --> 00:12:12,562
I left home when I was 18,
changed my name, met Phelps, eloped.

150
00:12:12,631 --> 00:12:15,532
We told his family
my father was dead.

151
00:12:15,601 --> 00:12:17,694
Soon that won't be a lie.

152
00:12:17,770 --> 00:12:21,866
You talk about Sam like
he means nothing to you.

153
00:12:26,045 --> 00:12:29,503
[Sighs] Well, occasionally,
if I'm havin' a good day...

154
00:12:29,581 --> 00:12:32,414
and the sun is shinin',

155
00:12:32,484 --> 00:12:34,577
I might think of him
and remember some small,

156
00:12:34,653 --> 00:12:36,883
pleasant moment
from my earliest days.

157
00:12:36,955 --> 00:12:39,583
The way he'd call me
sweet baby girl. [Chuckles]

158
00:12:39,658 --> 00:12:43,253
But mostly I remember
how he destroyed absolutely everyone...

159
00:12:43,328 --> 00:12:46,058
who made the mistake
of getting close to him.

160
00:12:48,667 --> 00:12:50,601
He'll do it to you too,
you know.

161
00:12:52,704 --> 00:12:56,140
Be very careful
dredging the past, Adam.

162
00:12:57,209 --> 00:13:00,508
You might not like
what comes up.

163
00:13:15,394 --> 00:13:17,328
[Sighs]

164
00:14:04,810 --> 00:14:06,744
I'm here to see
Sam Cayhall.

165
00:14:22,127 --> 00:14:24,061
- Briefcase.
- Oh.

166
00:14:30,035 --> 00:14:31,969
Spread your legs,
please.

167
00:14:36,542 --> 00:14:38,476
- Sergeant Packer.
- Adam Hall.

168
00:14:40,112 --> 00:14:42,046
This way, please.

169
00:14:49,755 --> 00:14:51,780
[Door Buzzer]

170
00:14:54,126 --> 00:14:57,186
- Not a good day to see Sam.
- Why is that?

171
00:14:57,262 --> 00:15:01,528
Prison attorney just called.
Judge ruled. He dies in 28 days.

172
00:15:02,768 --> 00:15:05,931
I'll get Sam.

173
00:15:06,004 --> 00:15:07,938
This way.

174
00:15:14,279 --> 00:15:16,213
[Lock Opening]

175
00:15:19,418 --> 00:15:21,352
Catch up.

176
00:15:24,389 --> 00:15:27,358
I'm gonna lock this door.
Sam'll be in, in a minute.

177
00:15:27,426 --> 00:15:29,360
Thanks.

178
00:15:46,011 --> 00:15:47,911
[Lock Opening]

179
00:15:52,217 --> 00:15:55,618
- Move on.
- [Sam] Get out.

180
00:16:03,862 --> 00:16:05,830
Who the hell are you?

181
00:16:05,897 --> 00:16:09,765
Adam Hall. I'm a lawyer
with Kravitz and Bane, Chicago.

182
00:16:09,835 --> 00:16:12,395
You Jew boys never quit, do you?

183
00:16:12,471 --> 00:16:14,803
I'm not Jewish.

184
00:16:14,873 --> 00:16:17,398
How can you work
for Kravitz and Bane?

185
00:16:17,476 --> 00:16:20,206
- Well, we're an equal
opportunity employer.
- Really?

186
00:16:20,278 --> 00:16:24,840
I know you got
about 150 partners up there.

187
00:16:24,916 --> 00:16:26,907
How many of 'em are women?

188
00:16:27,986 --> 00:16:30,284
I don't really know.
Maybe a dozen.

189
00:16:30,355 --> 00:16:33,324
Oh, so you got less
than ten percent women.

190
00:16:33,391 --> 00:16:35,723
How many nigger partners you got?

191
00:16:37,162 --> 00:16:39,096
We have four African-American partners.

192
00:16:39,164 --> 00:16:42,964
Well, that's nice. How many
Jewish-American partners you got?

193
00:16:43,034 --> 00:16:46,094
- About 80%?
- I don't really know.
It doesn't make a difference to me.

194
00:16:46,171 --> 00:16:48,105
Well, it makes
a big difference to me.

195
00:16:48,173 --> 00:16:51,939
I was always embarrassed to be
represented by such blatant bigots.

196
00:16:52,010 --> 00:16:56,470
Yeah. Well, I think a lot of people
would probably find it appropriate.

197
00:16:56,548 --> 00:16:59,039
- Why are you so nervous?
- I'm not nervous.

198
00:16:59,117 --> 00:17:01,779
You afraid I'm gonna come
through that screen and get you?

199
00:17:01,853 --> 00:17:05,016
How many death penalty cases
have you handled?

200
00:17:05,090 --> 00:17:07,456
This is my first. [Clears Throat]

201
00:17:07,526 --> 00:17:12,020
Oh, great. The Jew bastards sent
a greenhorn to save me.

202
00:17:12,097 --> 00:17:16,500
I killed some of their people,
and now they wanna kill me.

203
00:17:16,568 --> 00:17:18,798
I always expected it.

204
00:17:18,870 --> 00:17:20,804
You admit that you killed
the Kramer kids?

205
00:17:20,872 --> 00:17:23,636
Who the hell are you to ask me
a question like that?

206
00:17:23,708 --> 00:17:25,699
The jury said I did it.

207
00:17:25,777 --> 00:17:29,304
The appeals court said the jury
was right. That's all that matters.

208
00:17:31,783 --> 00:17:33,717
How old are you, there, Mr. Hall?

209
00:17:33,785 --> 00:17:35,980
Twenty-six.

210
00:17:36,054 --> 00:17:39,546
- I'd like to go over
your legal position...
- Born in '69.

211
00:17:39,624 --> 00:17:41,558
That's correct. Looking at your
legal position, I've come up with...

212
00:17:41,626 --> 00:17:43,560
- Where?
- In Memphis.

213
00:17:43,628 --> 00:17:47,120
- L... Listen, I'd prefer
to stick to the, uh...
- You grew up there, did you?

214
00:17:47,199 --> 00:17:49,531
I grew up in a lot of places,
mainly southern California.

215
00:17:49,601 --> 00:17:52,195
Mm-hmm.
Your family still there?

216
00:17:52,270 --> 00:17:55,637
[Sighs] Mom's remarried;
and she lives in Portland.

217
00:17:57,475 --> 00:17:59,739
And your sister.

218
00:17:59,811 --> 00:18:02,371
I believe her name would be Carmen.

219
00:18:07,419 --> 00:18:09,353
College. Berkeley.

220
00:18:17,929 --> 00:18:20,864
How did you know?

221
00:18:20,932 --> 00:18:24,333
The voice.
You sound just like your daddy.

222
00:18:26,304 --> 00:18:28,465
Why'd you come here?

223
00:18:28,540 --> 00:18:31,065
He sent me.

224
00:18:31,142 --> 00:18:34,839
I don't have a choice.
But I am gonna save you.

225
00:18:34,913 --> 00:18:37,438
- Save me? [Laughs]
- Yeah.

226
00:18:37,515 --> 00:18:40,848
This from the son of a man
that blew his own brains out?

227
00:18:40,919 --> 00:18:43,251
Go to hell,
you little piece of shit.

228
00:18:43,321 --> 00:18:46,256
You know who you're talkin' to?
Save me? Why, shit.

229
00:18:46,324 --> 00:18:49,020
You don't look like you could save
a turkey from Thanksgiving.

230
00:18:49,094 --> 00:18:53,224
Go on, get the hell outta here.
Try to save your own sorry ass.

231
00:18:53,298 --> 00:18:56,790
I am the only person on this earth who
gives a damn whether you live or die.

232
00:18:56,868 --> 00:19:00,099
Now, you are gonna sign this contract
agreeing to be my client,

233
00:19:00,171 --> 00:19:02,935
or you will be dead in 28 days.

234
00:19:04,743 --> 00:19:06,768
[Laughs]

235
00:19:10,715 --> 00:19:15,277
We're all a bit taken aback at how huge
this case has suddenly become.

236
00:19:15,353 --> 00:19:17,583
Uh, what's so huge about it?

237
00:19:17,656 --> 00:19:21,114
Oh, I know the Clarion-Ledger
is not the Chicago Tribune,

238
00:19:21,192 --> 00:19:24,753
but in our small pond,
it's everything.

239
00:19:25,830 --> 00:19:27,764
Uh, I'm lost.

240
00:19:28,833 --> 00:19:32,030
Certainly you've seen
